---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';

const post1Url = '/blog/best-keurig-alternatives';
const post3Url = '/blog/quit-keurig-pods-7-day-plan';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Keurig Cost Per Cup vs Bulk Brew Methods | The Brewdown"
  description="Keurig cost per cup vs French press, pour-over, and drip, with every assumption spelled out. Adjust beans, pods, and habits in our calculator."
>
  <article class="mx-auto max-w-3xl px-[var(--gutter)] py-10 md:py-14">
    <p class="font-mono text-xs uppercase tracking-wide text-ink-3">
      <a href="/blog" class="link-brewdown">Keurig alternatives series</a>
      · The Brewdown
    </p>
    <h1 class="mt-2 font-display text-4xl font-bold tracking-tight text-ink md:text-5xl">
      Keurig vs French Press, AeroPress, Pour-Over, and Drip: Real Cost Per Cup
    </h1>
    <p class="mt-4 text-lg text-ink-2">
      Transparent keurig cost per cup math you can verify, aligned to The Brewdown calculator defaults.
    </p>

    <div class="prose-brewdown mt-10 space-y-10 text-ink-2">
      <section class="space-y-4">
        <h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold text-ink">What a Keurig cup actually costs (and what you're comparing against)</h2>
        <p>
          This post answers one question: <strong class="font-medium text-ink">ingredient cost per cup</strong>,
          not total cost of ownership. For cumulative charts that include machine spend and
          café visits, use the calculator. Here we isolate what you pay for coffee in the cup.
        </p>
        <p>
          At Brewdown defaults, a K-Cup runs <strong class="font-medium text-ink">$0.80</strong> per cup in
          ingredients alone. Bulk methods cluster around <strong class="font-medium text-ink">$0.33 to $0.46</strong>
          depending on grams per cup and brew style. That is roughly half the pod line on beans alone, before
          you factor in machine upfront. Once you know the math, see
          <a href={post1Url} class="link-brewdown">which Keurig alternative fits your household</a>
          for taste, time, and cleanup tradeoffs.
        </p>
        <p>
          Below: every assumption in a table, the formulas step by step, and sensitivity checks for beans
          price, pod sales, and cups per day. Electricity, water, milk, and your time are excluded so the
          comparison stays apples to apples.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="space-y-4">
        <h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold text-ink">Assumptions used in this comparison</h2>
        <p>
          Every number maps to Brewdown calculator defaults or is labeled illustrative. If your cart looks
          different, swap any number in the calculator.
        </p>
        <div class="overflow-x-auto rounded-lg border border-[var(--line)] bg-paper-2 shadow-md">
          <table class="w-full min-w-[36rem] text-left text-sm">
            <thead>
              <tr class="border-b border-[var(--line)] font-mono text-xs uppercase tracking-wide text-ink-3">
                <th class="px-4 py-3 font-medium">Assumption</th>
                <th class="px-4 py-3 font-medium">Value</th>
                <th class="px-4 py-3 font-medium">Notes</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody class="divide-y divide-[var(--line)]">
              <tr>
                <td class="px-4 py-3 font-medium text-ink">Coffee price (bulk)</td>
                <td class="px-4 py-3">$15.00 per lb</td>
                <td class="px-4 py-3"></td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td class="px-4 py-3 font-medium text-ink">K-Cup price</td>
                <td class="px-4 py-3">$0.80 per pod</td>
                <td class="px-4 py-3"></td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td class="px-4 py-3 font-medium text-ink">Cup size (drip)</td>
                <td class="px-4 py-3">10 g coffee</td>
                <td class="px-4 py-3">6 oz cup equivalent</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td class="px-4 py-3 font-medium text-ink">Cup size (French press)</td>
                <td class="px-4 py-3">12 g</td>
                <td class="px-4 py-3"></td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td class="px-4 py-3 font-medium text-ink">Cup size (pour-over)</td>
                <td class="px-4 py-3">11 g</td>
                <td class="px-4 py-3"></td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td class="px-4 py-3 font-medium text-ink">Cup size (bean-to-cup)</td>
                <td class="px-4 py-3">14 g</td>
                <td class="px-4 py-3"></td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td class="px-4 py-3 font-medium text-ink">AeroPress (illustrative)</td>
                <td class="px-4 py-3">11 g</td>
                <td class="px-4 py-3">Same beans price; not a separate calculator preset</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td class="px-4 py-3 font-medium text-ink">Pods per cup</td>
                <td class="px-4 py-3">1</td>
                <td class="px-4 py-3">Standard K-Cup</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td class="px-4 py-3 font-medium text-ink">Grams per pound</td>
                <td class="px-4 py-3">453</td>
                <td class="px-4 py-3">Internal conversion constant</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td class="px-4 py-3 font-medium text-ink">Machine costs</td>
                <td class="px-4 py-3">See method table below</td>
                <td class="px-4 py-3">Upfront; not amortized in per-cup ingredient math</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td class="px-4 py-3 font-medium text-ink">Shop drinks</td>
                <td class="px-4 py-3">4/month default</td>
                <td class="px-4 py-3">Ongoing but separated from ingredient-only table</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td class="px-4 py-3 font-medium text-ink">Comparison horizon (cumulative)</td>
                <td class="px-4 py-3">60 months</td>
                <td class="px-4 py-3"></td>
              </tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>
        <p>
          Your grocery receipt may not match $15/lb or $0.80 per pod. That is expected.
          <a href="/" class="link-brewdown">Replace any number in the calculator</a>
          with your actual beans price, K-Cup box cost, and grams per cup.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="space-y-4">
        <h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold text-ink">How we calculate cost per cup</h2>
        <p>
          <strong class="font-medium text-ink">Bulk methods:</strong>
        </p>
        <p class="rounded-lg border border-[var(--line)] bg-paper-2 px-4 py-3 font-mono text-sm text-ink shadow-sm">
          ingredient cost per cup = grams per cup × (cost per lb ÷ 453)
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong class="font-medium text-ink">Pods:</strong>
        </p>
        <p class="rounded-lg border border-[var(--line)] bg-paper-2 px-4 py-3 font-mono text-sm text-ink shadow-sm">
          ingredient cost per cup = cost per pod × pods per cup
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong class="font-medium text-ink">Worked example (French press):</strong>
          12 g × ($15 ÷ 453) = $0.397, rounded to <strong class="font-medium text-ink">$0.40</strong>
          in prose. You can plug your own numbers into the same formula.
        </p>
        <p>
          This section does <strong class="font-medium text-ink">not</strong> include machine upfront cost,
          café spend, or pour-over filters (annual consumables default to $0 in the calculator). Brewdown
          puts machine cost on day one in cumulative comparisons; this post isolates the ingredient line
          for a clean keurig vs french press cost and keurig vs drip coffee cost snapshot. Read the
          <a href="/about" class="link-brewdown">full Brewdown cost model</a>
          for what the 60-month chart includes.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="space-y-4">
        <h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold text-ink">Keurig vs alternatives: ingredient cost per cup</h2>
        <p>
          Results below use the assumptions table. These are k cup cost per cup and bulk-method equivalents
          at default settings, not a verdict on total household spend.
        </p>
        <div class="overflow-x-auto rounded-lg border border-[var(--line)] bg-paper-2 shadow-md">
          <table class="w-full min-w-[28rem] text-left text-sm">
            <thead>
              <tr class="border-b border-[var(--line)] font-mono text-xs uppercase tracking-wide text-ink-3">
                <th class="px-4 py-3 font-medium">Method</th>
                <th class="px-4 py-3 font-medium">Grams or pods per cup</th>
                <th class="px-4 py-3 font-medium">Ingredient cost per cup</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody class="divide-y divide-[var(--line)]">
              <tr>
                <td class="px-4 py-3 font-medium text-ink">K-Cup (Keurig)</td>
                <td class="px-4 py-3">1 pod</td>
                <td class="px-4 py-3">$0.80</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td class="px-4 py-3 font-medium text-ink">Drip</td>
                <td class="px-4 py-3">10 g</td>
                <td class="px-4 py-3">~$0.33</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td class="px-4 py-3 font-medium text-ink">Pour-over</td>
                <td class="px-4 py-3">11 g</td>
                <td class="px-4 py-3">~$0.36</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td class="px-4 py-3 font-medium text-ink">AeroPress</td>
                <td class="px-4 py-3">11 g (illustrative)</td>
                <td class="px-4 py-3">~$0.36</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td class="px-4 py-3 font-medium text-ink">French press</td>
                <td class="px-4 py-3">12 g</td>
                <td class="px-4 py-3">~$0.40</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td class="px-4 py-3 font-medium text-ink">Bean-to-cup</td>
                <td class="px-4 py-3">14 g</td>
                <td class="px-4 py-3">~$0.46</td>
              </tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>
        <p>
          Bulk methods cluster around half the pod ingredient cost at these defaults. Bean-to-cup uses more
          coffee per cup (14 g) but still lands below $0.80 on ingredients alone. Keurig vs pour over cost
          and keurig vs french press cost both favor bulk beans at every row in this table.
        </p>
        <div class="rounded-lg border border-[var(--line)] bg-paper-2 px-5 py-4 shadow-md">
          <p class="font-display font-bold text-ink">At 2 cups per day</p>
          <p class="mt-2">
            Ingredient savings vs K-Cups using pour-over as the example: 2 × ($0.80 − $0.36) × 30 days ≈
            <strong class="font-medium text-ink">$26/month</strong> on beans alone.
            <a href="/" class="link-brewdown">See your monthly savings in the calculator</a>
            with your cup count and preferred bulk method.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="space-y-4">
        <h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold text-ink">Upfront machine cost: why the cheapest cup is not always the cheapest year one</h2>
        <p>
          Ingredient math is only half the story. Machine cost hits your budget on day one in Brewdown's
          model, not spread invisibly across per-cup figures.
        </p>
        <div class="overflow-x-auto rounded-lg border border-[var(--line)] bg-paper-2 shadow-md">
          <table class="w-full text-left text-sm">
            <thead>
              <tr class="border-b border-[var(--line)] font-mono text-xs uppercase tracking-wide text-ink-3">
                <th class="px-4 py-3 font-medium">Method</th>
                <th class="px-4 py-3 font-medium">Default machine cost</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody class="divide-y divide-[var(--line)]">
              <tr><td class="px-4 py-3">French press</td><td class="px-4 py-3">$30</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="px-4 py-3">Pour-over</td><td class="px-4 py-3">$40</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="px-4 py-3">AeroPress (illustrative)</td><td class="px-4 py-3">~$35</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="px-4 py-3">Drip</td><td class="px-4 py-3">$120</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="px-4 py-3">K-Cup brewer</td><td class="px-4 py-3">$120</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="px-4 py-3">Bean-to-cup</td><td class="px-4 py-3">$800</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>
        <p>
          French press wins on both ingredients and upfront gear vs a Keurig brewer at defaults. Drip and
          Keurig share a similar $120 machine default, but drip ingredient cost is lower. Bean-to-cup demands
          real upfront spend; the case for switching depends on volume and how long you keep the machine.
        </p>
        <p>
          Consider two cups per day over 60 months: pods vs French press. Ingredient savings accumulate every
          month; the $30 press vs $120 brewer gap is a one-time hit on day one. The crossover on total
          cumulative cost is easier to see than to hand-calculate.
          <a href="/" class="link-brewdown">Compare cumulative costs on the chart</a>
          with pods and bulk brew (French press preset) selected, then scroll the 60-month horizon.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="space-y-4">
        <h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold text-ink">What changes the comparison (beans, cups, and pod sales)</h2>
        <p>
          <strong class="font-medium text-ink">Beans at $10/lb vs $20/lb.</strong> French press recalculates
          to roughly <strong class="font-medium text-ink">$0.26 to $0.53</strong> per cup (12 g × price ÷
          453). Wider range than pods, but the top end still sits below a $0.80 K-Cup at default.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong class="font-medium text-ink">Pods at $0.55 (sale) vs $0.95 (premium).</strong> K-Cup
          ingredient cost moves with the box, but bulk methods still win on beans at almost any reasonable
          beans price. A good sale narrows the gap; it rarely closes it at two cups per day.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong class="font-medium text-ink">Cups per day.</strong> Ingredient savings scale linearly with
          volume. At one cup per day, machine upfront matters more relative to monthly beans. At three or
          more, ingredient delta dominates faster.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong class="font-medium text-ink">Takeaway:</strong> If you are asking is keurig cheaper than
          brewing coffee on ingredients alone, bulk methods win at defaults and across most realistic price
          swings. Pod sales help; they do not flip the default math.
          <a href="/" class="link-brewdown">Open the calculator and adjust the assumptions</a>
          for beans price, K-Cup price, and cups per day.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="space-y-4">
        <h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold text-ink">Ingredient cost is only part of the picture</h2>
        <p>
          Most calculator presets assume <strong class="font-medium text-ink">4 shop drinks per month</strong>
          alongside home brewing. Better coffee at home may reduce café visits; Brewdown tracks shop spend as
          a separate line so you do not double-count against ingredient tables.
        </p>
        <p>
          If you grab a latte on the commute twice a week, home ingredient savings still matter, but shop
          drinks belong in the model honestly. When you model your household, count café trips per method
          rather than assuming zero.
          <a href="/" class="link-brewdown">Set shop drinks honestly per method</a>
          in the calculator alongside your pod and bulk inputs.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="space-y-6">
        <h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold text-ink">FAQ: Keurig pricing and comparisons</h2>

        <div class="space-y-2">
          <h3 class="font-display text-lg font-bold text-ink">How much does a K-Cup cost per cup?</h3>
          <p>
            At Brewdown defaults, <strong class="font-medium text-ink">$0.80</strong> per pod. Sales, store
            brand multipacks, and premium roasts move that number. Divide your box price by pod count for your
            actual k cup cost per cup.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="space-y-2">
          <h3 class="font-display text-lg font-bold text-ink">Is Keurig cheaper than drip coffee?</h3>
          <p>
            On ingredient cost: no at defaults (~$0.80 pod vs ~$0.33 drip). On machine upfront: similar
            ($120 brewer for both in the calculator). Drip wins the per-cup beans line; total savings depend
            on cups per day and how long you keep the gear.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="space-y-2">
          <h3 class="font-display text-lg font-bold text-ink">Keurig vs French press: which is cheaper?</h3>
          <p>
            French press wins on ingredients (~$0.40 vs $0.80) and machine cost ($30 vs $120 at defaults).
            Cleanup is more hands-on. If the math convinces you and you want a low-friction switch,
            <a href={post3Url} class="link-brewdown">switch to French press in a week</a>
            with our day-by-day plan.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="space-y-2">
          <h3 class="font-display text-lg font-bold text-ink">Does expensive coffee make pods a better deal?</h3>
          <p>
            Worked example at $20/lb bulk: French press at 12 g ≈ $0.53 per cup. A $0.80 pod is still
            higher on ingredients. You would need very cheap pods or very expensive specialty beans before
            pods catch up on beans alone.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="space-y-2">
          <h3 class="font-display text-lg font-bold text-ink">Should I include the Keurig machine in cost per cup?</h3>
          <p>
            Brewdown does not hide machine cost inside per-cup ingredient math. The brewer appears as
            upfront spend on day one of the cumulative chart. That keeps pod vs bulk ingredient tables clean
            while still showing total cost over 60 months when you are ready.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="space-y-2">
          <h3 class="font-display text-lg font-bold text-ink">How do I compare my actual spending?</h3>
          <p>
            Open the calculator, select pods and one bulk method, then
            <a href="/" class="link-brewdown">enter your pod box price and local beans</a>.
            Match grams per cup to how you actually brew. The chart adds machine and shop lines on top of
            ingredients.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="rounded-lg border border-[var(--line)] bg-paper-2 px-5 py-6 shadow-md">
        <h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold text-ink">Adjust the assumptions and see your crossover</h2>
        <p class="mt-3">
          This post uses ingredient-only snapshots. The calculator adds machine cost, daily volume, and café
          spend on a 60-month chart. Select pods vs one bulk method from the results table, then change beans
          price and K-Cup price to match your cart.
        </p>
        <p class="mt-4">
          <a
            href="/"
            class="inline-block rounded-md bg-brand px-5 py-2.5 text-sm font-semibold text-white shadow-sm transition-colors hover:bg-brand/90"
          >
            Open the calculator and adjust the assumptions
          </a>
        </p>
        <p class="mt-4 text-sm">
          Next steps:
          <a href={post1Url} class="link-brewdown">pick a method from the alternatives guide</a>
          ·
          <a href={post3Url} class="link-brewdown">7-day plan to quit pods</a>
        </p>
        <p class="mt-4 text-sm text-ink-3">
          Verify the math here, then let your real receipts and morning habits finish the argument.
        </p>
      </section>
    </div>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .link-brewdown {
    color: var(--brand);
    text-decoration: underline;
    text-decoration-color: color-mix(in srgb, var(--brand) 40%, transparent);
    text-underline-offset: 2px;
  }

  .link-brewdown:hover {
    text-decoration-color: var(--brand);
  }
</style>
